WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.970 --> 00:00:04.542
MALE SPEAKER:
Welcome, Google world.

00:00:04.542 --> 00:00:06.250
My name is [? Sunny Sani, ?]
and I'm here

00:00:06.250 --> 00:00:08.740
to introduce Daniel Shapiro.

00:00:08.740 --> 00:00:11.100
Daniel Shapiro is one of
the world's leading experts

00:00:11.100 --> 00:00:13.610
in negotiation and
conflict resolution

00:00:13.610 --> 00:00:16.210
and is founder and director
of the world renowned Harvard

00:00:16.210 --> 00:00:18.540
International
Negotiation Program.

00:00:18.540 --> 00:00:21.270
He has appeared on dozens of
radio and television shows

00:00:21.270 --> 00:00:23.382
and has contributed to
the "New York Times,"

00:00:23.382 --> 00:00:27.630
"O, the Oprah Magazine," and
other popular publications.

00:00:27.630 --> 00:00:29.500
He is the recipient
of numerous awards,

00:00:29.500 --> 00:00:31.830
including the American
Psychological Association's

00:00:31.830 --> 00:00:34.170
Early Career Award
and the Cloke-Millen

00:00:34.170 --> 00:00:36.080
Peacemaker of the Year award.

00:00:36.080 --> 00:00:40.226
The World Economic Forum named
him a Young Global Leader.

00:00:40.226 --> 00:00:42.100
And he is here today to
talk about the tenets

00:00:42.100 --> 00:00:45.040
of his new book, "Negotiating
the Nonnegotiable."

00:00:45.040 --> 00:00:47.930
And without further
ado, Daniel Shapiro.

00:00:47.930 --> 00:00:49.701
DANIEL SHAPIRO: Thank you.

00:00:49.701 --> 00:00:52.750
Thank you, [? Sunny. ?]
So thank you.

00:00:52.750 --> 00:00:56.340
It is great to be here
with all of you today.

00:00:56.340 --> 00:01:00.485
So let me start with my
association with Google.

00:01:00.485 --> 00:01:02.610
So I have a few, but let
me tell you the one that's

00:01:02.610 --> 00:01:04.500
most prominent in my mind.

00:01:04.500 --> 00:01:07.440
It was probably close
to 10 years back.

00:01:07.440 --> 00:01:09.080
I was in those
mountains of Switzerland

00:01:09.080 --> 00:01:12.280
at Davos at the World Economic
Forum's annual meeting.

00:01:12.280 --> 00:01:16.840
And the hippest, the coolest
event of the whole time there,

00:01:16.840 --> 00:01:21.380
for their annual summit in
January, was the Google party.

00:01:21.380 --> 00:01:25.090
And guess who did not get an
invitation to the Google party?

00:01:25.090 --> 00:01:26.740
Loser here.

00:01:26.740 --> 00:01:30.025
So some of my friends,
who were a little bit more

00:01:30.025 --> 00:01:32.570
in the circle, said,
we'll sneak you in.

00:01:32.570 --> 00:01:35.620
And so somehow I get
shuffled in a backdoor

00:01:35.620 --> 00:01:37.140
into the Google party.

00:01:37.140 --> 00:01:39.040
I'm there talking
with Charlie Rose

00:01:39.040 --> 00:01:40.455
and a couple of other people.

00:01:40.455 --> 00:01:42.330
And we start getting
into, so what do you do?

00:01:42.330 --> 00:01:43.350
And I knew Charlie Rose.

00:01:43.350 --> 00:01:44.724
I turned to the
person beside me.

00:01:44.724 --> 00:01:45.650
So what do you do?

00:01:45.650 --> 00:01:47.895
And this person says,
I work at Google.

00:01:47.895 --> 00:01:48.720
I said, oh, really?

00:01:48.720 --> 00:01:49.761
What do you do at Google?

00:01:49.761 --> 00:01:52.270
And he says, I founded it.

00:01:52.270 --> 00:01:53.165
It was Larry Page.

00:01:53.165 --> 00:01:53.664
Yeah.

00:01:53.664 --> 00:01:55.472
So I went, oh.

00:01:55.472 --> 00:01:57.100
So I'm sneaking into your party.

00:01:57.100 --> 00:01:58.970
He goes, yeah, pretty much.

00:01:58.970 --> 00:02:01.280
And anyway, the rest of
our time there at Davos,

00:02:01.280 --> 00:02:03.670
literally, it was the
most awkward situation.

00:02:03.670 --> 00:02:06.300
Somehow, I found myself
sitting directly next to him

00:02:06.300 --> 00:02:07.400
again and again.

00:02:07.400 --> 00:02:11.260
And again, I could feel
him going, who is this guy?

00:02:11.260 --> 00:02:12.820
But I enjoyed
meeting your founder.

00:02:12.820 --> 00:02:14.490
I'm sure he does not
remember me at all,

00:02:14.490 --> 00:02:16.770
although I very much member him.

00:02:16.770 --> 00:02:20.281
So let me start by asking
all of you a question.

00:02:20.281 --> 00:02:21.030
And you know what?

00:02:21.030 --> 00:02:22.290
There are some of you over here.

00:02:22.290 --> 00:02:23.540
I'm going to be very annoying.

00:02:23.540 --> 00:02:26.260
Would you mind just
coming over this way,

00:02:26.260 --> 00:02:30.880
just so we are one happy
family here at Google.

00:02:30.880 --> 00:02:33.250
So just a show of
hands-- how many

00:02:33.250 --> 00:02:37.789
of you in the past six
months have-- feel free.

00:02:37.789 --> 00:02:39.372
Feel free just to
walk in front of me.

00:02:39.372 --> 00:02:41.140
Yeah.

00:02:41.140 --> 00:02:43.900
How many of you in
the past six months

00:02:43.900 --> 00:02:47.120
have experienced an
emotionally-charged conflict?

00:02:47.120 --> 00:02:48.980
Raise your hands.

00:02:48.980 --> 00:02:50.280
Yes?

00:02:50.280 --> 00:02:51.220
Yes?

00:02:51.220 --> 00:02:51.720
OK.

00:02:51.720 --> 00:02:52.300
Your hand-- OK.

00:02:52.300 --> 00:02:52.550
Good.

00:02:52.550 --> 00:02:53.070
OK.

00:02:53.070 --> 00:02:54.200
So you are human beings.

00:02:54.200 --> 00:02:55.050
Good.

00:02:55.050 --> 00:02:56.460
Let me ask you
one more question,

00:02:56.460 --> 00:02:59.000
which will seem like
a total non sequitur,

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:00.920
but I believe it is not.

00:03:00.920 --> 00:03:03.395
Anybody here know
what a poplar tree is?

00:03:03.395 --> 00:03:04.950
A poplar tree?

00:03:04.950 --> 00:03:05.450
Yeah.

00:03:05.450 --> 00:03:07.962
So what's a poplar tree, sir?

00:03:07.962 --> 00:03:12.300
AUDIENCE: A tree that has
fairly roundish flowers on it.

00:03:12.300 --> 00:03:14.910
DANIEL SHAPIRO: OK, so a tree
with fairly roundish flowers

00:03:14.910 --> 00:03:15.410
on it.

00:03:15.410 --> 00:03:17.260
I'll have to trust
you on that one.

00:03:17.260 --> 00:03:19.100
It's a deciduous tree.

00:03:19.100 --> 00:03:20.520
Few of us in this
room would have

00:03:20.520 --> 00:03:23.900
much of any interest in what
is a poplar tree if it weren't

00:03:23.900 --> 00:03:26.180
for the fact that there
was a single poplar

00:03:26.180 --> 00:03:28.840
tree that sat right at that
border between North and South

00:03:28.840 --> 00:03:30.202
Korea.

00:03:30.202 --> 00:03:32.410
And each year, this little
poplar tree would blossom,

00:03:32.410 --> 00:03:33.790
and it would grow.

00:03:33.790 --> 00:03:37.490
And as it would grow, it would
block the South Koreans' view

00:03:37.490 --> 00:03:41.150
of the Bridge of No Return, the
conduit between North and South

00:03:41.150 --> 00:03:42.720
Korea.

00:03:42.720 --> 00:03:44.854
So each year, out would
march a small team

00:03:44.854 --> 00:03:46.270
of South Korean
soldiers, and they

00:03:46.270 --> 00:03:48.150
would go to trim this tree.

00:03:48.150 --> 00:03:50.780
It was a security concern,
and this was fine.

00:03:50.780 --> 00:03:56.250
Year after year after year,
until August 6th, 1976,

00:03:56.250 --> 00:03:59.470
when the usual team of South
Korean soldiers, they go out.

00:03:59.470 --> 00:04:02.100
They're trimming the tree
for about 10 minutes.

00:04:02.100 --> 00:04:04.800
Along comes a lieutenant
from the North Korean side

00:04:04.800 --> 00:04:08.160
with a much larger team
of North Korean soldiers.

00:04:08.160 --> 00:04:09.900
The lieutenant from
the North walks up

00:04:09.900 --> 00:04:12.100
the lieutenant from the South.

00:04:12.100 --> 00:04:14.910
You try and trim this
tree, we're going to shoot!

00:04:14.910 --> 00:04:16.209
And sorry.

00:04:16.209 --> 00:04:18.029
We're going to shoot!

00:04:18.029 --> 00:04:22.560
And they literally chase
away the South Korean team.

00:04:22.560 --> 00:04:25.410
But this is a security concern.

00:04:25.410 --> 00:04:27.350
And it does not stop
the South Koreans

00:04:27.350 --> 00:04:29.339
from trying to trim this tree.

00:04:29.339 --> 00:04:30.880
They come back about
two weeks later,

00:04:30.880 --> 00:04:35.170
now with a much larger team
of South Korean soldiers, US

00:04:35.170 --> 00:04:38.770
soldiers, and UN
officials, and all

00:04:38.770 --> 00:04:42.350
there for the single
purpose of what?

00:04:42.350 --> 00:04:44.520
Trying to trim this
damn tree, you know?

00:04:44.520 --> 00:04:47.920
And they start trimming once
again for about 10 minutes.

00:04:47.920 --> 00:04:50.520
Along comes that
lieutenant from the North,

00:04:50.520 --> 00:04:52.450
this time with a
much, much larger team

00:04:52.450 --> 00:04:54.570
of North Korean soldiers.

00:04:54.570 --> 00:05:00.060
You try and trim this tree,
we are going to shoot.

00:05:00.060 --> 00:05:01.640
This did not stop
the South Koreans

00:05:01.640 --> 00:05:03.750
from trying to trim this tree.

00:05:03.750 --> 00:05:07.180
And for those of you who might
remember what happened next,

00:05:07.180 --> 00:05:10.450
this turned into a
bloody, bloody mess.

00:05:10.450 --> 00:05:12.020
There were a number
of South Koreans

00:05:12.020 --> 00:05:14.980
who were injured in the
circumstance, two US

00:05:14.980 --> 00:05:21.620
Soldiers not just shot--
decapitated, caught on camera,

00:05:21.620 --> 00:05:24.420
broadcast around the world.

00:05:24.420 --> 00:05:26.570
I was presenting this
case fairly recently

00:05:26.570 --> 00:05:28.630
in my home
institution in Boston.

00:05:28.630 --> 00:05:30.210
And after I was
presenting the case

00:05:30.210 --> 00:05:33.650
to some international military
leaders, some lawyers, business

00:05:33.650 --> 00:05:36.430
people, and so on, I was
walking out of the room.

00:05:36.430 --> 00:05:38.770
And this one gentleman
comes chasing after me,

00:05:38.770 --> 00:05:40.570
face as red as you can imagine.

00:05:40.570 --> 00:05:41.410
Shapiro!

00:05:41.410 --> 00:05:41.910
That's me.

00:05:41.910 --> 00:05:43.770
Shapiro, I don't
think you understand!

00:05:43.770 --> 00:05:45.720
I don't think you
understand, he says.

00:05:45.720 --> 00:05:47.250
I was there.

00:05:47.250 --> 00:05:49.690
I was at West Point,
the US military college,

00:05:49.690 --> 00:05:51.110
at that point in time.

00:05:51.110 --> 00:05:53.470
He says, I knew those boys.

00:05:53.470 --> 00:05:55.450
I knew their families.

00:05:55.450 --> 00:05:58.790
He said, we were not
just feeling grief

00:05:58.790 --> 00:06:01.420
at the loss of our soldiers.

00:06:01.420 --> 00:06:05.050
He says, we were feeling
utter, utter humiliation

00:06:05.050 --> 00:06:07.690
at the way our boys died.

00:06:07.690 --> 00:06:10.220
And surprise, surprise,
this situation

00:06:10.220 --> 00:06:13.020
then reaches the highest
of the high in the United

00:06:13.020 --> 00:06:17.190
States, the White House, where
then-President Ford was faced

00:06:17.190 --> 00:06:21.370
with a very difficult decision.

00:06:21.370 --> 00:06:22.655
What do you do?

00:06:22.655 --> 00:06:23.280
What do you do?

00:06:23.280 --> 00:06:25.150
And he turns to
his lead advisor.

00:06:25.150 --> 00:06:27.420
And his lead advisor
basically says,

00:06:27.420 --> 00:06:29.880
well, you know what I think
we should do, Mr. President?

00:06:29.880 --> 00:06:34.340
I think we should bomb
the North Koreans.

00:06:34.340 --> 00:06:36.340
And the president
thinks about it

00:06:36.340 --> 00:06:38.810
and decides that a more
appropriate strategy

00:06:38.810 --> 00:06:41.920
would be to simply try
to cut down this tree.

00:06:41.920 --> 00:06:43.840
So now back to the scene.

00:06:43.840 --> 00:06:47.550
On August 21st, 1976,
some two weeks later,

00:06:47.550 --> 00:06:51.930
comes 813 human power, manpower
as they sometimes call it,

00:06:51.930 --> 00:06:54.450
F-4 fighters, F-5 fighters.

00:06:54.450 --> 00:06:58.200
They had a 64-man armed
platoon trained in taekwondo.

00:06:58.200 --> 00:07:02.840
They had three B-52 bombers
circling around overhead

00:07:02.840 --> 00:07:07.082
with the single purpose of what?

00:07:07.082 --> 00:07:08.290
Trying to cut down this tree.

00:07:08.290 --> 00:07:09.930
And do they do it?

00:07:09.930 --> 00:07:10.840
Yes.

00:07:10.840 --> 00:07:11.950
How long does it take?

00:07:11.950 --> 00:07:13.880
About one hour.

00:07:13.880 --> 00:07:15.600
Was there further incident?

00:07:15.600 --> 00:07:17.180
No.

00:07:17.180 --> 00:07:21.730
But as I was learning about
this story, what struck me most

00:07:21.730 --> 00:07:26.080
is that this was literally
almost World War III.

00:07:26.080 --> 00:07:27.600
Literally almost World War III.

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:28.183
And over what?

00:07:28.183 --> 00:07:30.160
Over a tree?

00:07:30.160 --> 00:07:35.060
And obviously, it's over much,
much more than just a tree.

00:07:35.060 --> 00:07:37.380
But it begs two
fundamental questions

00:07:37.380 --> 00:07:40.860
that connect all of us together,
two basic questions that we're

00:07:40.860 --> 00:07:42.220
going to focus on today.

00:07:42.220 --> 00:07:44.090
One, why-- there we go.

00:07:44.090 --> 00:07:49.160
One, why do we get stuck in
emotionally-charged conflicts?

00:07:49.160 --> 00:07:52.390
And two, how do we get out?

00:07:52.390 --> 00:07:54.340
And, I mean, if you
look at the situation,

00:07:54.340 --> 00:07:56.310
if this were the United
States and Canada

00:07:56.310 --> 00:08:01.020
fighting over a tree,
five minutes, it's done.

00:08:01.020 --> 00:08:02.740
There's something
strange that happens

00:08:02.740 --> 00:08:05.080
when we get into
emotionally-charged conflicts,

00:08:05.080 --> 00:08:07.750
whether at work or
in the home life

00:08:07.750 --> 00:08:10.130
or in the international realm.

00:08:10.130 --> 00:08:13.170
So with that, the more
specific purpose for today

00:08:13.170 --> 00:08:15.540
is twofold-- well,
let me go back one.

00:08:15.540 --> 00:08:19.610
Twofold-- it's to present a
framework based upon research

00:08:19.610 --> 00:08:22.630
that I've been conducting
over the past 20 years.

00:08:22.630 --> 00:08:27.150
Just two modest goals for today
connected to my new book-- one,

00:08:27.150 --> 00:08:31.130
how do you guard against
the most fundamental mindset

00:08:31.130 --> 00:08:32.770
that traps us in conflict?

00:08:32.770 --> 00:08:34.210
What is that mindset?

00:08:34.210 --> 00:08:36.280
How do you guard against it?

00:08:36.280 --> 00:08:38.720
And second big
purpose of today--

00:08:38.720 --> 00:08:42.650
there tend to be these
emotional forces that pull us

00:08:42.650 --> 00:08:46.010
toward adversarial
relations, even when it

00:08:46.010 --> 00:08:47.650
doesn't make sense.

00:08:47.650 --> 00:08:49.260
What are those forces?

00:08:49.260 --> 00:08:51.900
And how might you try
to deal with them?

00:08:51.900 --> 00:08:53.650
We're not going to go
into the full depth.

00:08:53.650 --> 00:08:54.450
The book is there.

00:08:54.450 --> 00:08:56.908
But for sure, I'm going to give
you some of the basic ideas

00:08:56.908 --> 00:08:58.770
so you have a good
sense of what they are.

00:08:58.770 --> 00:09:03.040
So before jumping into our talk
formally for the day, quickly,

00:09:03.040 --> 00:09:06.312
where do these ideas come from?

00:09:06.312 --> 00:09:08.020
The ideas I'll be
talking about with you,

00:09:08.020 --> 00:09:09.950
they come from two
different places.

00:09:09.950 --> 00:09:13.660
One, from laboratory research
that myself and colleagues have

00:09:13.660 --> 00:09:16.430
done, fieldwork,
global field work

00:09:16.430 --> 00:09:18.030
around conflict resolution.

00:09:18.030 --> 00:09:19.830
My own work has
been with, really,

00:09:19.830 --> 00:09:22.220
a vast variety of
different groups,

00:09:22.220 --> 00:09:24.630
everybody from civil
society organizations,

00:09:24.630 --> 00:09:28.390
grassroots organizations,
families in crisis,

00:09:28.390 --> 00:09:33.120
to working with heads of state
and CEOs of major businesses.

00:09:33.120 --> 00:09:34.950
And by the way,
I can promise you

00:09:34.950 --> 00:09:36.760
but one thing-- by
the end of our time

00:09:36.760 --> 00:09:39.135
together, although I've had
these various different kinds

00:09:39.135 --> 00:09:41.560
of experiences, my
greatest learning

00:09:41.560 --> 00:09:45.300
has come from negotiating with
three of the hardest bargainers

00:09:45.300 --> 00:09:47.164
that the world has ever seen.

00:09:47.164 --> 00:09:48.830
And you will have to
believe me on this.

00:09:48.830 --> 00:09:51.030
It is these guys right here.

00:09:51.030 --> 00:09:53.230
And these are my children.

00:09:53.230 --> 00:09:56.497
Noah's the oldest, Zachary
second, Liam is the third.

00:09:56.497 --> 00:09:58.080
And you will have
to trust me-- day in

00:09:58.080 --> 00:10:00.730
and day out, they test
every one of these skills.

00:10:00.730 --> 00:10:04.600
I truly believe that most things
are negotiable except maybe

00:10:04.600 --> 00:10:06.250
with my children.

00:10:06.250 --> 00:10:08.950
So anyway, my purpose for
showing you that slide, though,

00:10:08.950 --> 00:10:12.610
is to say that, yes, what we
will be talking about today

00:10:12.610 --> 00:10:16.810
is relevant in the corporate
context, in the business world.

00:10:16.810 --> 00:10:18.310
It's just as relevant
whether you're

00:10:18.310 --> 00:10:21.990
trying to negotiate with
mom or dad, brother, sister,

00:10:21.990 --> 00:10:24.700
whoever it might be at home,
as well-- romantic partner.

00:10:24.700 --> 00:10:28.290
So with that, let's
jump into the problem.

00:10:28.290 --> 00:10:30.460
The problem is
this-- how should you

00:10:30.460 --> 00:10:34.180
resolve an
emotionally-charged conflict?

00:10:34.180 --> 00:10:38.400
Now, these conflicts
impose a tremendous cost

00:10:38.400 --> 00:10:41.380
on any organization.

00:10:41.380 --> 00:10:43.880
Most people don't even recognize
the extent of the costs

00:10:43.880 --> 00:10:46.790
that conflict brings
to your organization.

00:10:46.790 --> 00:10:49.030
When you look at the financial
spreadsheets for most

00:10:49.030 --> 00:10:51.840
organizations, you
see, often, one line

00:10:51.840 --> 00:10:56.602
which deals with conflict--
legal fees, litigation.

00:10:56.602 --> 00:10:58.060
And yet at the same
time, there are

00:10:58.060 --> 00:11:02.390
all of these hidden costs of
poorly dealing with conflict.

00:11:02.390 --> 00:11:04.497
You have all of the
poor decision-making--

00:11:04.497 --> 00:11:05.455
what's your first name?

